        Sudanland_land_h3_type_t19:"1- Bedouinism:",

        Sudanland_land_h3_type_t19_p2:" (Black clay soil): It is a black clay plain characterized by high fertility, a high degree of humidity in the fall, and it retains water for long periods. It is the most suitable for digging holes, but its disadvantages are that it is affected by thirst, which makes it susceptible to cracking; and consequently, the plants in it are affected and may wither, so it needs continuous irrigation. It is also heavy on plants; because due to its cohesion, it may prevent the roots from absorbing the water that it traps between its particles, and the drainage of water in it is very slow, which leads to poor ventilation when the soil holes are filled with water. This soil is found in central and eastern Sudan, and represents the most important areas for growing cotton and mechanized rain-fed agriculture. It also represents an important source of forest products, especially firewood and gum arabic. Most of Sudan's production of corn (the main food crop) is grown in this soil.",

        Sudanland_land_h3_type_t20:"2- The black grouse (Celtic grouse):",
        Sudanland_land_h3_type_t20_p1:" It is a clay plain mixed with small stones, characterized by good fertility and good water retention and does not crack easily, so the plants in it are tolerant of thirst, and moderate irrigation is sufficient for it. This land is characterized by a moderate temperature and very good ventilation and is considered one of the best soils for agriculture. The group of Celtic sedimentary soils is often found on the banks of rivers and valleys, and these soils are characterized by their high fertility due to their annual renewal.           ",

